Description: Achieving and maintaining Strike Force Interoperability (SFI) requires disciplined engineering,
system integration, and configuration management at both the platform (ship or shore station) and strike
force level (Carrier Strike Group/ Amphibious Readiness Group). The Command, Control, Communications,
Computers, Combat Systems, Intelligence, Surveillance, Reconnaissance (C5ISR) Modernization Program
(C5IMP) pillar of SFI ensures that deploying strike force ships receive modernized and interoperable warfighting
capabilities in order to meet theater operational requirements. This project funds engineering assessments of
proposed C5I capability improvements to determine maturity for installation as well as technical and schedule
risks associated with proposed hardware and software changes. This project directly supports the requirements
of the Fleet C5I Modernization Policy (per COMUSFLTFORCOM/COMPACFLT Inst. 4720.3) which assigns
responsibilities to NAVSEA 05H to assess operational risks associated with C5ISR modernization in both
afloat and ashore units in support of the Optimized Fleet Response Plan (OFRP). The deliverables of this
project are created by determining the maturity, through engineering analysis, of the critical linchpins needed
to achieve interoperability for each proposed C5IMP capability improvement item to be installed in a ship's
baseline, developing installation recommendations of C5I system upgrades for the Fleet Commanders, and
researching and analyzing installation or operating problems. This includes a review of Warfare System Ship
Change Documents (SCDs). SFI coordinates closely with the FLTCDRs and TYCOMs as well as other members
of the C5IMP community to address, coordinate, and resolve C5IMP modernization issues, thereby reducing risk
and enhancing readiness and effectiveness of deploying ships and strike groups. The SFI C5IMP pillar focuses
on key milestones such as Baseline Locking Events (BLEs), Planned Not Authorized (PNA) reviews, and Strike
Group (SG)/Amphibious Ready Group (ARG) Analysis Reports which are Fleet required events. The BLEs, PNA
Reviews, and SG/ARG Analysis Reports are the primary work products for C5IMP.

Emerging warfighting requirements and the development of required hardware and software changes between
CNO Availability periods require SFI to administer an electronic change control board (eCCB) to facilitate the
request, review, and approval of proposed Baseline changes. SFI maintains the Afloat Master Planning System
(AMPS) data for the approximately 285 active Battle Force ships, in addition to initial configuration of the New
Construction ships entering the Fleet each year. SFI maintains and continuously updates C5ISR Configuration
Control for every ship based on projection of ships' operating/maintenance schedules at SG deployment. Due
to changing operational needs, these schedules frequently change causing availability extensions, deferrals,
cancellations, or delays. SFI extracts and formats the data in AMPS to develop the BLE and PNA Review
presentations which enables the Fleet commanders and TYCOMs to make informed modernization decisions.
CUSFFC/CPF Instruction 4720.3C designates NAVSEA 05 as the executing agent for the two NCMCs held
each year where Fleet Commanders, TYCOMs, SYSCOMs and supporting personnel gather to discuss advance

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions, Article Quantities in Each)                                                        FY 2026   FY 2026      FY 2026
                                                                                                                   FY 2024   FY 2025    Base      OOC          Total
plans, coordinate near term modernization plans, and coordinate shore and shipboard installations to ensure
support prior to deployments, resolve schedule issues and establish priorities. Major issues identified at each
NCMC are reported to a joint FFC/CPF flag/SES panel.

.

